  <entry>
    <id>https://community.sap.com/t5/sap-cap-blog-posts/june-developer-challenge-cap-knowledge-task-18-rfc-for-uuids/bc-p/14426553#M778</id>
    <title>Re: June Developer Challenge - CAP Knowledge - Task 18 - RFC for UUIDs</title>
    <updated>2026-06-24T15:10:03.147000+02:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Dan_Wroblewski</name>
      <uri>https://community.sap.com/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/72</uri>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;P&gt;&lt;a href="https://community.sap.com/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/168423"&gt;@SachinArtani&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;I think DJ is looking for the RFC number only, let's say "123" and not "RFC123", which is what I think you hashed.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;a href="https://community.sap.com/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/53"&gt;@qmacro&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;There are 2 RFCs that I found that might be relevant, lets call them A and B. In Capire, A is mentioned, and I am assuming the one you want. But I have seen on the web this article where it says that A is outdated and we now use B.&lt;BR /&gt;&lt;BR /&gt;&lt;/P&gt;&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&lt;HR /&gt;&lt;SPAN&gt;"GUIDs are defined by IETF standards (RFCs). For many years, developers referenced&amp;nbsp;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;RFC A&amp;nbsp;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;SPAN&gt;(published July 2005), but this document has been formally&amp;nbsp;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;obsoleted&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;SPAN&gt;&amp;nbsp;by&amp;nbsp;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;RFC B&amp;nbsp;&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;SPAN&gt;(published May 2024).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/SPAN&gt;&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&lt;P&gt;Since you wrote what is the CAP UUID compliant with, I assume we have to go with A, since technically that is what CAP is promising.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;</content>
    <link href="https://community.sap.com/t5/sap-cap-blog-posts/june-developer-challenge-cap-knowledge-task-18-rfc-for-uuids/bc-p/14426553#M778"/>
    <published>2026-06-24T15:10:03.147000+02:00</published>
  </entry>
  <entry>
